'''Shimazu Kuni no Miyatsuko''' (島津国造, also read as Shimazu Kokuzō) was a {{ill|kuni no miyatsuko|ja|国造|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (provincial governor) governing the {{ill|Shima Province|ja|志摩国|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.
== Overview == === Ancestry === According to the ''{{ill|Sendai Kuji Hongi|ja|先代旧事本紀|qq=draft|qq=draft}}'' ("Kuni no Miyatsuko Hongi" section), during the reign of {{ill|Emperor Seimu|ja|成務天皇|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Izumo Kasaya no Mikoto|ja|出雲笠夜命|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, the grandson of {{ill|Sahini Ashini|ja|佐比邇足尼|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, who was also an ancestor of the {{ill|Izumo no Kuni no Miyatsuko|ja|Izumo Province 造|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, was appointed as Shimazu Kuni no Miyatsuko.
=== Clan === The Shimazu Kuni no Miyatsuko belonged to the {{ill|Shima clan|ja|島氏|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (Shima-uji, with the title {{ill|Ason (title)|ja|直|qq=draft|qq=draft}}). They were related to the {{ill|Futakata Kuni no Miyatsuko|ja|二方国造|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. Even after the end of the {{ill|kuni no miyatsuko|ja|国造|qq=draft|qq=draft}} system, they continued to serve as {{ill|gunryō|ja|郡領|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (district governors) in {{ill|Tōshi District|ja|答志郡|qq=draft|qq=draft}} during the {{ill|Medieval Japan|ja|中世|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.<ref>Ryo Ota, "Shima," in ''Seishi Kakeizu Daijiten'' (1936), p. 2846.</ref> Based on genealogies and entries in the ''Kuni no Miyatsuko Hongi,'' they are generally regarded as related to the {{ill|Izumo Omi|ja|出雲臣|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.
== Territory == === Governed Region === The territory governed by the Shimazu Kuni no Miyatsuko corresponds to the area known in ancient times as "Shima (津) Province," later becoming {{ill|Shima Province|ja|志摩国|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, now the {{ill|Shima region|ja|志摩地方|qq=draft|qq=draft}} of {{ill|Mie Prefecture|ja|三重県|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.
== Patron Deity == The clan's deity is enshrined at the {{ill|Ise Grand Shrine|ja|伊雑宮|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, the {{ill|Ichinomiya|ja|一宮|1=Ichinomiya|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (highest-Ranking shrine) of Shima Province, located in the former {{ill|Tōshi District|ja|答志郡|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.
=== Associated Shrines === * {{ill|Saminaga Shrine|ja|佐美長神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}} *: Located in {{ill|Isobe, Mie|ja|磯部町恵利原|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Shima City|ja|志摩市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, this is a {{ill|Shikinai-sha|ja|式内社|1=Shikinaisha|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. Like their relatives the {{ill|Futakata Kuni no Miyatsuko|ja|二方国造|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, they worshipped {{ill|Ōtoshi no Kami|ja|大歳神|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.<ref name="houga" />
== References == === Notes === {{reflist|refs= <ref name="houga">{{ill|Toshio Hōga|ja|宝賀寿男|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, "Chapter 5: Developments in Izumo Province before Emperor Sujin," in ''Research on Ancient Clans ⑯: The Izumo and Haji Clans—The Rise and Fall of the Original Izumo Kingdom'' (Aogaki Publishing, 2020), pp. 193–194.</ref> }}
=== Sources === * ''Kokushi Daijiten'' (Yoshikawa Kōbunkan) * Taro Sakamoto and Kunio Hirano, ''Nihon Kodai Shizoku Jinmei Jiten'' (Yoshikawa Kōbunkan) * ''Nihon Kodai Jinmei Jiten'' (Yoshikawa Kōbunkan) * ''Nihonshi Kōjiten'' (Yamakawa Shuppansha) * ''Shintō Daijiten'' (Rinsen Shoin) * {{ill|Toshio Hōga|ja|宝賀寿男|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, ''Izumo-shi, Haji-shi: The Rise and Fall of the Original Izumo Kingdom'' (Hōrei Publishing) * Ryo Ota, ''Seishi Kakeizu Daijiten'' Vol. 3 (Kokuminsha) == See Also == * {{ill|List of Kuni no Miyatsuko|ja|国造の一覧|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
